         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nMathematics is present everywhere, and we often experience it without even noticing. This leads us to our first exercise:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_lab_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_lab question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-microscope\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_lab\"><b>Practice 1: Where are they?</b><br /><br />Based on what we have studied so far, look around you and identify situations in which you could apply addition or multiplication.</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": " "
            },
            {
               "text": "At first glance, the exercise seems to suggest choosing between addition and multiplication. However, as we have already seen, multiplication is nothing more than repeated addition (<htcite0>). Therefore, it is not possible to completely separate multiplication from addition.\n\nAlthough this might give the impression that the exercise is incorrect, in reality it introduces the central theme of this text: the combined use of multiplication and addition to understand nature.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "eaa59295-fb80-4c33-b1e4-bcdf3c11dabf",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
